<!-- COURSE HOME -->
<div class="panel active" id="p-welcome">
<div class="paste">Canvas Page — Course Home · Pin to top · Student and Instructor Facing</div>
<div class="page-flag">
  <div class="page-eyebrow">Slow News, Smart Citizens · Ten-Week Module</div>
  <h1 class="page-title">Welcome to the Conversation</h1>
  <p class="page-deck">A media literacy practice, a physical publication, and a room full of people who came prepared to think together.</p>
</div>
<div class="page-rule"></div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>What This Module Is</h3>
  <p>Slow News, Smart Citizens is a ten-week layer in this course. It is not a separate course running inside the one you are already in. It is a recurring practice that runs alongside your other work throughout the quarter, asking you to pay sustained attention to one corner of the world, to think carefully about what you find there, and to make something from it at the end that you and your classmates can hold in your hands.</p>
  <p>The practice has two layers. The first is digital: a reading list, discussion boards, and written assignments that develop your capacity to read the information environment critically and write about it clearly. The second is analog: a hand-kept notebook, weekly observations made with pen and paper, and a final physical publication assembled by the class together. Both layers matter. Neither one is optional.</p>
  <div class="pull">"The goal is not to distrust the news. The goal is to read it the way a person who knows something reads it, and then to sit down with other people and talk about what you found."</div>
  <p>Those two layers are not in competition. They are the same project. The digital work trains you to notice things. The analog work gives you a place to record them slowly, live with them, and make something from them that exists in the world as a physical object, something you made by hand with your classmates.</p>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>Why Now</h3>
  <p>The history of news is a history of technology changing what journalism is possible, what audiences expect, and what counts as being informed. Each major technology transition produced the same argument: this technology is destroying journalism, or this technology is saving it. Each time, the answer was neither. The technology changed the conditions. Journalism figured out what it was inside the new conditions. It always did, imperfectly, with gains and losses that were not evenly distributed.</p>
  <p>We are in another one of those transitions now. Generative AI is changing the conditions again. A significant portion of what you encounter online is now generated, summarized, or routed by AI systems. The chain from claim to original source, which journalists and careful readers have always used to evaluate information, is being hidden or collapsed by the act of synthesis. When a large language model produces an answer to your question, the source disappears. The answer appears. You receive rather than decide.</p>
  <p>This module does not take the position that AI is destroying journalism or saving it. It takes the position that technology changes the conditions, and that human beings, individually and collectively, still determine what they do inside those conditions. Slow news and media literacy are two responses to the same changed conditions. They are not in tension with each other. They are the same project.</p>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>The Slow News Conversation</h3>
  <p>There is a form of conversation that predates every media technology: people sitting down together, having read something, to talk about what they noticed. A coffee klatch. A reading group. A newsroom morning meeting. A kitchen table argument about something in the paper. The form is ancient. In some ways it is the most durable thing journalism has ever produced, more durable than any format or platform or delivery mechanism.</p>
  <p>Every session of this module opens with something like that conversation. You arrive having followed your beat for another week, having written something by hand about what you noticed, and you sit down with your classmates and talk about it. The five critical moves give the conversation structure. The notebook gives it memory. The physical publication gives it a form that lasts beyond the quarter.</p>
  <p>That conversation is the antidote this course is trying to build. Not a technology, not a platform, not an app. A practice of sitting down, reading carefully, writing by hand, and talking to another person about what you found. You cannot opt out of it after the fact. You have to opt in, on purpose, every week.</p>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>How the Module Is Organized</h3>
  <p>Five modules, two weeks each, one critical move per module. Every module has an overview page, a notebook prompt page, a discussion board, and one major assignment. The notebook runs underneath everything, all ten weeks, and is submitted complete at the end of Module 5.</p>
  <div class="arc">
    <div class="arc-row"><div class="arc-wk c1">Module 1</div><div class="arc-content"><div class="arc-title">Description (Weeks 1–2)</div><div class="arc-sub">Choose your beat. Describe what it says right now. Map where it comes from. Beat Source Map due.</div></div></div>
    <div class="arc-row"><div class="arc-wk c1">Module 2</div><div class="arc-content"><div class="arc-title">Analysis (Weeks 3–4)</div><div class="arc-sub">Track how your beat's coverage works and moves. Trace the AI footprint. Story Arc Analysis due.</div></div></div>
    <div class="arc-row"><div class="arc-wk c2">Module 3</div><div class="arc-content"><div class="arc-title">Interpretation (Weeks 5–6)</div><div class="arc-sub">Bring your knowledge to bear on what the coverage cannot say. Find your cluster. Interpretive Brief due.</div></div></div>
    <div class="arc-row"><div class="arc-wk c2">Module 4</div><div class="arc-content"><div class="arc-title">Evaluation (Weeks 7–8)</div><div class="arc-sub">What is at stake, and who is paying? Equity Assessment and Cluster Proposal due.</div></div></div>
    <div class="arc-row"><div class="arc-wk c3">Module 5</div><div class="arc-content"><div class="arc-title">Engagement (Weeks 9–10)</div><div class="arc-sub">Draft, peer review, revise, and assemble. State of the World and physical publication due at the assembly session.</div></div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>What You Will Need</h3>
  <div class="spec-grid">
    <div class="spec-card"><div class="spec-card-label">The Notebook</div><p>A physical notebook with unlined or lightly lined pages. At least 40 pages. A three-dollar composition book works as well as an expensive sketchbook. Your instructor will name it for this course. Whatever it is called, it is kept by hand, it is yours, and it runs all ten weeks.</p></div>
    <div class="spec-card"><div class="spec-card-label">A Beat</div><p>An ongoing area of public life connected to your field, your interests, or your experience. Not a topic in the abstract. A live, developing area of news with a traceable primary source. You choose this in Week 1 and follow it for ten weeks. By Week 10 you will know things about it that almost no one who encountered it only in headlines does.</p></div>
    <div class="spec-card"><div class="spec-card-label">The Publication Artboard</div><p>For the final assembly: 11-by-17 paper is the ideal artboard. Folded once, it becomes a four-page tabloid. Used flat in landscape, it is a broadsheet spread. Used flat in portrait, it is a magazine page. 8.5-by-11 works as the atomic unit, one page per entry. Your instructor will specify the format for this course.</p></div>
    <div class="spec-card"><div class="spec-card-label">Your Phone Camera</div><p>Weekly notebook entries are submitted as phone photos uploaded to Canvas. Low friction, good enough quality for weekly review. The final publication is photographed carefully after assembly and submitted as the archival record. The physical object is yours to keep.</p></div>
  </div>
</div>
