<!-- EVOLUTION OF NEWS AND PUBLISHING -->
<div class="panel" id="p-evolution">
<div class="paste">Canvas Page — News and Publishing: A Brief History · Concept Overview · All versions</div>
<div class="page-flag">
  <div class="page-eyebrow">Concept Overview</div>
  <h1 class="page-title">News and Publishing: How We Got Here</h1>
  <p class="page-deck">Technology changes the conditions. Human beings determine what they do inside them. A brief history of that argument, and what it means for where we are now.</p>
</div>
<div class="page-rule"></div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>The Argument That Keeps Recurring</h3>
  <p>Every time a significant communication technology has emerged and spread, the same argument has followed it. This technology is destroying journalism. Or: this technology is saving journalism. The argument has been made about the penny press, the telegraph, the photograph, radio, television, cable news, the internet, social media, and now generative AI. In every case the answer has been neither, and in every case people have had to figure out what journalism was inside the new conditions the technology created.</p>
  <p>That is not technological determinism, which holds that technology drives social change and human beings simply adapt to it. It is something more complicated and more honest: technology creates new possibilities and new constraints, and human beings, institutions, economies, and cultures make choices inside those possibilities and constraints. The outcome is not written by the technology. It is made by the people navigating it.</p>
  <div class="pull">"The printing press did not determine what the Reformation would be. It created conditions inside which the Reformation became possible. Human beings, with their convictions and their conflicts, determined what happened next."</div>
  <p>This distinction matters for how you approach your beat. You are not simply a bystander to technological change in your field. You are one of the people making choices about how to read, what to follow, what to trust, and what to say. This module is practice for making those choices deliberately.</p>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>Five Moments Worth Understanding</h3>

  <h4>The Print Era: Reproducibility and Public Knowledge</h4>
  <p>Before movable type, information traveled slowly, expensively, and with significant gatekeeping at every stage of reproduction. The printing press did not simply speed up that process. It changed who could produce information, what it cost to distribute it, and who counted as an audience. It made public knowledge possible in a new sense: a claim that appeared in print could be encountered by many people in the same form, at roughly the same time, and evaluated against other printed claims.</p>
  <p>The authority problem that media literacy still addresses was born here. If anyone can print something, how do readers know what to believe? The answer that developed across several centuries was not inevitable. Named authors, identifiable publishers, correction culture, the separation of news from advertising: these practices were made, contested, and remade. They are still being made and contested now.</p>

  <h4>Radio and Television: Presence and the Credible Voice</h4>
  <p>Radio introduced something print could not: the voice in real time. Broadcast journalism inherited the credibility frameworks of print but added the dimension of presence. You heard something as it happened, or you heard someone describe it as it happened, which created the experience of presence even when the listener was hundreds of miles away. Television added the image, and the image changed what a credible source looked like. The visual grammar of authority in journalism was invented largely by broadcasters who were figuring it out as they went.</p>

  <h4>The Internet: Abundance and the Collapse of Gatekeeping</h4>
  <p>The internet did not simply add speed to existing journalism. It collapsed the economic model that had sustained it for a century. The bundled newspaper and the mass-audience broadcast depended on advertising revenue attached to a captive audience. The internet distributed both publishing capacity and audience attention across a vastly larger landscape. The gatekeeping function that editors and publishers had always performed became simultaneously impossible to maintain and impossible to replace with anything better.</p>
  <p>What emerged was not chaos exactly, but a profoundly different information environment: more voices, more access to primary sources, more perspectives on any given story, and simultaneously more noise, more manipulation, and more content produced for engagement rather than understanding.</p>

  <h4>The iPad and the Magazine That Was Not Saved</h4>
  <p>In 2010, the iPad arrived and publishers believed it would save the magazine. The logic was reasonable: a beautiful touch-screen device capable of carrying full-resolution photography and long-form text seemed like the natural heir to the print magazine's form. Publishers invested heavily in tablet applications. The apps were often gorgeous. Readers downloaded them.</p>
  <p>Nobody paid for them at scale, and the model collapsed. What survived on the tablet was not the magazine. It was the feed. The infinite, scrollable, algorithmically sorted feed that had already begun reshaping how people encountered information on the web. The lesson was not that readers did not want magazines. It was that the economic and behavioral logic of the screen was different from the logic of print, and that logic could not simply be overridden by making a digital object look like a paper one.</p>
  <p>The physical publication this course produces is not attempting to recreate what the iPad could not. It is doing something different: making a deliberate, hand-assembled, room-specific object that exists because a specific group of people made it, at a specific moment, about what they were actually watching in the world. That is not something an algorithm produces. It is not something AI generates. It is something a class makes together.</p>

  <h4>Social Media: The Algorithm as Editor</h4>
  <p>Social media introduced something genuinely new to the history of information: an editorial function that optimizes for engagement rather than accuracy, importance, or civic value. The algorithm does not have editorial standards in the journalistic sense. It has performance metrics. What gets amplified is what gets clicked, shared, and reacted to, regardless of whether those actions correlate with the information being true, useful, or worth a citizen's attention.</p>
  <p>This did not simply change how journalism was distributed. It changed what journalism had to compete with. A carefully reported, accurately sourced, nuanced account of a complex policy issue competes, in an algorithmic environment, against content designed to produce an immediate emotional response. The playing field is not level and was not designed to be.</p>

  <h4>Generative AI: The Collapsed Source Chain</h4>
  <p>Generative AI introduces a change that is different in kind from the previous transitions. Each of the earlier shifts changed how information was produced, distributed, or encountered. Generative AI changes the relationship between a claim and its origin. When a large language model synthesizes an answer to your question, it produces a response that may be accurate, partially accurate, or inaccurate. The reader has no reliable way to evaluate which, because the chain from answer to source has been collapsed by the synthesis.</p>
  <p>There is also something new in how AI-generated content is now delivered. Earlier technologies required some active choice on the reader's part: you bought the newspaper, you turned on the television, you searched for something. The emerging model of AI-generated summaries and agentic overviews operates differently. It arrives without being sought. It is, in many contexts, the default view rather than an option you selected. You are opting out rather than opting in. That shift in the presumption of consent is one of the more significant changes in the information environment of the mid-2020s, and it is worth noticing as a structural fact.</p>
  <p>The source chain, which the Analysis move in this course is designed to trace, has always been the foundation of media literacy practice. Named sources, bylines, publication standards, and correction culture all exist to make that chain visible and accountable. The Slow News practice is a response to the conditions in which that chain is being routinely hidden. It asks you to slow down enough to find the chain, trace it, and bring your own knowledge to bear on what you find at the other end.</p>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>Where This Leaves Us</h3>
  <p>The history of news is not a story of progress or decline. It is a story of recurring negotiation between new technological conditions and the persistent human need for reliable information about the shared world. Every generation has had to develop new practices for navigating its specific information environment. The slow news practice and the five critical moves are this course's contribution to that recurring project.</p>
  <p>You are not simply a reader of this history. You are inside it. The choices you make about what to follow, how carefully to read, what to trust, and what to contribute are part of what determines what journalism and public information become in the years ahead. This module is practice for making those choices deliberately, with attention, and with other people in the room.</p>
  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">A note for instructors outside journalism</div>
    <p>This page is written from a journalism perspective but the history it describes applies to every field that produces knowledge for public use: medicine, law, science, finance, design, education. Every discipline has its own version of the authority problem, the gatekeeping collapse, and the AI synthesis challenge. Consider asking students to identify the equivalent transitions in your field. The structural questions are the same. The specific examples will be theirs to name.</p>
  </div>
</div>
</div>

