<div class="panel" id="p-process">
<div class="paste">Canvas Page — The Five Critical Moves · Student Reference · Permanent · All versions</div>
<div class="page-flag">
  <div class="page-eyebrow">Student Reference — Keep This Open All Term</div>
  <h1 class="page-title">The Five Critical Moves</h1>
  <p class="page-deck">The sequence is the method. Each move requires the one before it. Start at the beginning, every time.</p>
</div>
<div class="page-rule"></div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>Where This Framework Comes From</h3>
  <p>The critical process used in this course is a five-step framework developed in media studies education across several decades. It draws on traditions of critical thinking, journalism education, media literacy scholarship, and the study of how knowledge is made and communicated in public life. It is not a checklist. It is a practice, and like any practice, it develops through repetition. The sequence matters: each move requires the one before it. A reader who jumps to evaluation before doing description tends to evaluate assumptions rather than evidence.</p>
  <p>The framework appears throughout the assigned reading in Richard Campbell's <em>Media and Culture</em>, which provides the foundational vocabulary for each move. The readings assigned week by week in this module are calibrated to deepen your understanding of each move as you practice it on your beat.</p>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>The Five Moves</h3>
  <div class="move-row"><div class="move-n">1</div><div class="move-body"><div class="move-title">Description</div><div class="move-q">"What does this actually say?" Account for what is present: the main claim, the evidence cited, the gap between what the headline promises and what the body delivers. Without reaction. Without evaluation. Just what is there. The most underrated step in everyday reading, and the most consistently skipped.</div></div></div>
  <div class="move-row"><div class="move-n">2</div><div class="move-body"><div class="move-title">Analysis</div><div class="move-q">"How does it work, and how did it get here?" Trace the structure: who produced it, how it was distributed, whose voices are present and absent, and what forces shaped its form. This is where the AI question lives. How did this reach me, and what did AI do to it along the way?</div></div></div>
  <div class="move-row"><div class="move-n">3</div><div class="move-body"><div class="move-title">Interpretation</div><div class="move-q">"What does it mean, in light of what you know?" Bring your disciplinary training, your field-specific knowledge, and your educated attention to bear on what your beat means. This is the move where your education becomes a contribution rather than background. What only you, with your training and your weeks of following this beat, can say about what this coverage means.</div></div></div>
  <div class="move-row"><div class="move-n">4</div><div class="move-body"><div class="move-title">Evaluation</div><div class="move-q">"Is it fair, adequate, and who pays the costs?" Make a reasoned judgment, grounded in evidence, named by a principle you can state and defend. Specific about who bears costs and who captures benefits. This is not reaction. It is accountable judgment, and it is different from having an opinion.</div></div></div>
  <div class="move-row"><div class="move-n">5</div><div class="move-body"><div class="move-title">Engagement</div><div class="move-q">"What do you do with what you know?" Produce something. Carry what you have learned into a form a public audience can use. The person who has done the first four moves carefully has earned the right to say something, and has the responsibility to say it clearly, with sources, and with accountability for what they claim.</div></div></div>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>The Moves and Your Notebook</h3>
  <p>The weekly notebook prompt uses the same three-part structure regardless of which module you are in. That structure maps onto the five moves across the term in a way that deepens as the module progresses:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>What I noticed</strong> begins with Description. Account for what is actually there before you react to it.</li>
    <li><strong>What moved</strong> is Analysis. What changed, what drove it, what structural forces are visible.</li>
    <li><strong>What I'm sitting with</strong> is the seed of Interpretation in early weeks, Evaluation in middle weeks, and Engagement in the final weeks. The same question, deepening over time.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>By Week 9, "what I'm sitting with" is not a naïve question about something you do not yet understand. It is a carefully formed question that eight weeks of beat work have made possible. That deepening is the arc of the notebook, and it is what makes the holistic assessment meaningful.</p>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>AI and the Moves</h3>
  <p>The Analysis move is where the AI question lives most naturally, but it runs through all five. When you ask "how did this reach me?" you are already asking about recommendation algorithms, AI summarization, and the collapse of the source chain. When you ask "what does my knowledge add?" you are supplying what AI synthesis cannot: disciplinary judgment, contextual understanding, and accountability for what you claim. When you ask "who bears the costs?" you are asking about the equity of AI infrastructure, AI labor, and AI-mediated coverage. When you produce the State of the World entry and the physical publication, you are making something human, sourced, and accountable in an environment full of content that is not.</p>
  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">The AI Observation Thread</div>
    <p>One persistent Discussion Board thread runs across all ten weeks of this module. Any time you encounter AI's visible role in how a news item was generated, summarized, recommended, or distributed, add one observation. One sentence on what you found; one sentence on how you knew, or how you were not sure. No argument required. Just the observation. Over ten weeks, that thread becomes a class record of how AI is actually operating in the information environment you navigate, more specific and varied than any single reading about AI and media could be.</p>
  </div>
</div>
</div>

