<div class="panel" id="p-analog">
<div class="paste">Canvas Page — The Slow News Practice · Student and Instructor Facing · Analog Layer · All versions</div>
<div class="page-flag">
  <div class="page-eyebrow">The Analog Layer</div>
  <h1 class="page-title">The Slow News Practice</h1>
  <p class="page-deck">Why the notebook is kept by hand, what the physical publication is for, and what the research says about slowing down on purpose.</p>
</div>
<div class="page-rule"></div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>Why Analog</h3>
  <p>The research on handwriting and learning is not ambiguous. Writing by hand, forming letters, choosing what to record, making a physical mark on a physical surface, engages the brain differently than typing. It slows the process of recording in a way that forces synthesis: you cannot write down everything, so you have to decide what matters. That decision is a cognitive act. It is, in a small way, the same act the critical process practices week after week.</p>
  <p>A 2024 study by researchers at the Norwegian University of Science and Technology confirmed what a well-established body of earlier research had found: handwriting activates more of the brain than typing, engages both fine motor systems and higher-order cognitive functions, and produces stronger memory encoding for conceptual material. The study did not suggest that typing is bad. It suggested that handwriting does something different, and that the difference is worth preserving in learning environments where screens have become the default for everything.</p>
  <p>This is why the notebook is kept by hand. Not as a performance of analog virtue, and not as a rejection of digital tools. The digital assignments in this module are submitted digitally, and you are reading these instructions on a screen right now. But the act of writing by hand in a notebook, slowly, with attention, on paper, is doing something for your thinking that the Canvas text box does not do. Both have a place in this course. They are doing different things, and both things matter.</p>
  <div class="pull">"Slowing down is not falling behind. It is the condition for knowing what you think."</div>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>The Notebook: How It Works</h3>
  <p>Your instructor has named the notebook for this course. Whatever it is called, the structure is the same every week. Before class, you write a brief entry in your notebook, between 150 and 250 words, using three prompts. The entry is written by hand. After you write it, you photograph it with your phone and upload the photo to Canvas before class begins.</p>
  <div class="journal">
    <div class="journal-label">Weekly Notebook Entry — Three Prompts · 150–250 words · By Hand · Photographed and Uploaded Before Class</div>
    <p><strong>What I noticed:</strong> One specific observation from this week's beat work. Not a summary of the news. A noticing. Something that surprised you, confused you, or changed how you see your thread. Specific enough that someone reading it a year from now would know exactly what you are describing.</p>
    <p><strong>What moved:</strong> One thing that changed in the story or the coverage this week, and what you think drove the change. Not the latest update. The thing that shifted, and your best account of why.</p>
    <p><strong>What I'm sitting with:</strong> The question you cannot yet answer. Specific enough that someone could actually help you think about it. Not "I wonder about AI" but something like: "I cannot figure out why the primary source stopped appearing in coverage after the third week, when the story is clearly still developing."</p>
  </div>
  <p>The instructor is not grading your handwriting. They are reading what you noticed, and whether your noticing is developing in specificity and depth across the ten weeks. At Week 10, you submit all ten entries compiled, photographed clearly and in order. The notebook is assessed holistically, as an arc, not entry by entry.</p>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>The Physical Publication</h3>
  <p>At the end of the module, the class assembles a physical publication together. This is the Slow News deliverable. It is the State of the World made into something you can hold. It is not a digital project printed out. It is assembled by hand, in the room, during the final session of the module, by the people who made it.</p>
  <p>The format is flexible by design, because the form should follow what the class made. The 11-by-17 sheet is the ideal artboard: folded, it becomes a four-page tabloid. Opened flat in landscape, it is a broadsheet. Opened flat in portrait, it is a magazine page. The 8.5-by-11 page is the atomic unit: one page, one entry, one week's worth of attention. A class publication can be as simple as one spread per cluster stapled together, or as elaborate as a fully designed eight-page tabloid. Your instructor will specify the minimum for this course.</p>
  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">What goes in the publication</div>
    <ul>
      <li>Your cluster's State of the World entry, the anchor piece</li>
      <li>Excerpts from your notebook, selected and arranged by hand</li>
      <li>Headlines, annotations, and drawings made by hand directly on the page</li>
      <li>Longer typed text, if needed, printed and cut and pasted in physically</li>
      <li>Photographs from the term, printed and placed by hand</li>
      <li>Found materials from your beat: clipped headlines, printed documents, anything that belongs to the story you followed</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>The 20-Page Version</h3>
  <p>In a ten-week course with two class sessions per week, there are twenty class meetings. The full version of the Slow News publication is designed with one page per class session: twenty pages, made across twenty sessions, assembled on the twentieth. Not all courses will reach twenty pages, and that is fine. What matters is that the publication is a genuine record of the quarter's work, drawn from the notebooks, the beat work, and the State of the World entries that have been building all term, not assembled at the last minute from material produced specifically for the deadline.</p>
  <div class="decision">
    <div class="decision-label">Three decisions your instructor has made for this course</div>
    <div class="d-item"><div class="d-num">1</div><div class="d-text"><strong>The notebook is called:</strong> [Instructor fills in — reporter's notebook, field journal, researcher's log, observer's record, or another name specific to this discipline and context]</div></div>
    <div class="d-item"><div class="d-num">2</div><div class="d-text"><strong>The publication format is:</strong> [Instructor fills in — 11x17 tabloid folded, 8.5x11 booklet, landscape broadsheet, or other]</div></div>
    <div class="d-item"><div class="d-num">3</div><div class="d-text"><strong>The publication minimum is:</strong> [Instructor fills in — e.g., one spread per cluster plus a cover, four pages minimum, or twenty pages for the full version]</div></div>
  </div>
</div>
</div>

