<div class="paste">Canvas Page — Module 1 Overview · Description · Weeks 1–2 · Instructor and Student Facing</div>
<div class="mod-header">
  <div class="mod-badge">Module 1 of 5</div>
  <h2 class="mod-title">Description</h2>
  <p class="mod-sub">Weeks 1 and 2 — "What does your beat actually say, right now?"</p>
  <div class="mod-meta">
    <div class="mod-meta-item">Move <span>Description</span></div>
    <div class="mod-meta-item">Weeks <span>1 and 2</span></div>
    <div class="mod-meta-item">Notebook entries <span>Two, one per week</span></div>
    <div class="mod-meta-item">Assignment <span>Beat Source Map, due end of Week 2</span></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>What Description Is</h3>
  <p>Description is the most underrated step in everyday reading, and the most consistently skipped. It asks you to account for what is actually in a story: the main claim, the evidence cited, the gap between what the headline promises and what the body delivers. Not what you think about it. Not what it reminds you of. Not whether you agree. Just what is there.</p>
  <p>Description is harder than it sounds because most reading is actually a process of confirmation. We read the headline, form an impression, and read the body looking for evidence of the impression we already have. Description reverses that. It asks you to hold your reaction in suspension long enough to see what is actually present. A person who can do that consistently reads news differently, and better, than someone who cannot.</p>
  <p>This module also asks you to choose your beat: the ongoing area of public life you will follow for ten weeks. The Beat Source Map, due at the end of Week 2, is the document that makes everything else possible. A careful map now makes the Interpretive Brief in Module 3 significantly easier to write with depth and specificity.</p>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>Week 1: Choosing and Naming Your Beat</h3>
  <h4>In class</h4>
  <p>Opening question: "What is your beat, and what does it say right now?" Each student names their beat in one sentence and their thread in one sentence, present tense and specific. No evaluation yet. Just what is there. The instructor listens for students who have chosen topics too broad to follow on a weekly basis and redirects toward a specific thread within the larger topic.</p>
  <h4>What a beat is</h4>
  <p>A beat is an ongoing area of public life that generates news continuously. Not a topic in the abstract. A live, developing field with a traceable primary source, a set of institutions or actors that keep producing new material, and a connection to something you already know from your studies, your experience, or your life. You will follow it for ten weeks. By Week 10 you will know things about it that almost no one who encountered it only in headlines does.</p>
  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">Three criteria for a good beat</div>
    <p><strong>Live:</strong> developing right now, with new information arriving each week. <strong>Traceable:</strong> you can find a primary source, a document, a study, an institution, a named actor generating the news. <strong>Connected:</strong> to your field, your training, your background, or your lived experience, so that the Interpretation move in Module 3 has something real to draw on.</p>
  </div>
  <h4>Beat examples across disciplines</h4>
  <p><strong>Journalism:</strong> A specific court case, policy debate, corporate investigation, or community issue traced from primary sources through specialist coverage to mainstream outlets. <strong>Sciences:</strong> How a specific category of research is being covered in the general press — clinical trials, environmental monitoring, energy technology. <strong>Business and finance:</strong> Labor organizing in a specific sector, a regulatory investigation, or a company's evolving public disclosures. <strong>Humanities and arts:</strong> Coverage of a cultural institution, an ongoing preservation effort, or a sustained artistic controversy. <strong>Any field:</strong> How your field's research or practice is being covered by mainstream media, and how AI is changing that coverage.</p>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h3>Week 2: Mapping the Source Architecture</h3>
  <h4>In class</h4>
  <p>Opening question: "Where does your beat's news come from, and how does it reach a general reader?" Students trace the three-layer source architecture of their beat. The instructor looks for students whose primary source layer is thin, since they will struggle with the Interpretation move in Module 3 without a more specific anchor in the underlying evidence.</p>
  <h4>The three source layers</h4>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Primary:</strong> The origin. A study, report, legal filing, company announcement, event. The thing that happened before anyone wrote about it.</li>
    <li><strong>Specialist:</strong> First coverage. Trade publications, specialist outlets, wire services. The people who cover this beat with expertise on a regular basis.</li>
    <li><strong>Mainstream:</strong> Where the general public encounters the story. National newspapers, broadcast outlets, social summaries. Often several steps removed from the primary source.</li>
  </ul>
  <h4>The AI footprint: do this audit now</h4>
  <p>When you find your beat's stories this week, note how they reached you. Was there an AI summary before the article? What did the summary say versus what the article said? Did an algorithm surface this story, or did you search for it directly? Students who do this audit carefully in Week 2 have richer and more specific material in their Story Arc Analysis and their State of the World entry than students who try to reconstruct it at the end.</p>
</div>
</div>

