<div class="page-rule"></div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Purpose</h3>
  <p>The Beat Source Map establishes the information architecture of your chosen beat: the three source layers, the structural pattern of coverage, the AI footprint, and your disciplinary angle. It is not a summary of the news. It is a map of where the news comes from, how it travels, and where AI enters the chain. A careful Source Map in Week 2 makes the Interpretive Brief in Module 3, the Equity Assessment in Module 4, and the State of the World entry in Module 5 significantly easier to write with depth and specificity.</p>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Before You Write: The Hand-Drawn Map</h3>
  <p>Before writing the typed submission, sketch your beat's source architecture by hand in your notebook. Draw the three layers. Draw where AI enters. Draw the path a story takes from primary source to your screen. The sketch does not need to be neat. It needs to be accurate. It is not submitted separately. It is preparation for the written map, and it often produces insights the written version then captures more clearly.</p>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Instructions: 400 to 500 words in prose</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Name the beat and the thread.</strong> One sentence each: the beat is the ongoing field, the thread is the specific developing story you are following right now. Present tense. Specific. Traceable to a primary source.</li>
    <li><strong>Map the three source layers.</strong> Primary source: who or what generates the original material — named institutions, documents, actors, events. Specialist layer: who covers it with expertise. Mainstream layer: where the general public encounters it. Name specific examples at each layer.</li>
    <li><strong>Trace the AI footprint.</strong> Where does AI enter your beat's information system — in recommendation, summarization, generation, or distribution? Make at least one specific, concrete observation about what AI does to your beat's coverage. Not a general statement about AI in news, but something specific to what you observed this week in this beat.</li>
    <li><strong>Name your disciplinary angle.</strong> One sentence connecting your field or background to this beat, specific enough to seed the Interpretive Brief in Module 3. Not "I study journalism" but "my training in [specific area] lets me see [specific thing] in this beat."</li>
    <li><strong>Name one structural pattern you already see.</strong> Something about how this beat's coverage works that you noticed in the first two weeks. Descriptive, not evaluative — an observation about structure, not a judgment about quality.</li>
  </ol>
</div>
