<div class="block">
  <h3>What Analysis Is</h3>
  <p>Analysis asks how coverage works structurally, not just what it says this week. How is it produced? Who decides what gets covered? How do stories travel from primary source to general audience, and what forces shape what the public sees and does not see? In Module 1, you mapped the source architecture at a single moment. In Module 2, you watch it move.</p>
  <p>The AI question lives most naturally inside Analysis. When you ask how a story reached you, you are already asking about recommendation algorithms, AI summarization, and the collapse of the source chain. What did the algorithm decide to surface for you versus what you found by searching directly? What did the AI summary say versus what the reported article said? Who is speaking in your beat's coverage and who is consistently absent, and what structural forces explain that pattern?</p>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Week 3: How Coverage Is Produced</h3>
  <p>Opening question for class: "What is one thing you now understand about how your beat's coverage is produced that you did not understand at Week 1?" Students share structural observations, not this week's news, but what they have learned about the system behind the news. The instructor listens for pattern recognition across the room: structural features that appear in multiple students' beats, suggesting something about how information systems operate across fields.</p>
  <p>Things to watch for in your beat this week: How far does coverage typically travel from its primary source before it reaches a general reader? Which outlets are doing original work and which are aggregating? Where does AI enter — in search, in social distribution, in summarization, in generation? What does the AI-mediated version of your beat's news look like compared to the reported version?</p>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Week 4: The Shape of Coverage</h3>
  <p>Opening question: "What is the most significant turn in your beat's coverage across the last four weeks, and what drove it?" Students report on the shape of coverage across the module so far, not on the latest update. What turned? What stalled? What disappeared from the news cycle, and why?</p>
  <p>A beat going quiet is not a failure of the assignment. It is information. Stories disappear from coverage not because they are resolved but because they lose the attention of the outlets that were covering them. That observation belongs in the Story Arc Analysis and eventually in the State of the World entry. A student who can name why a story went quiet has done something that most casual readers of that story have not.</p>
</div>
</div>

