</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>What Interpretation Is</h3>
  <p>Interpretation is the move that separates a careful reader from a casual one. It asks you to bring your disciplinary training, your field-specific knowledge, and your educated attention to bear on what your beat means — not what the coverage says it means, but what someone with your particular preparation can see that a general reader cannot.</p>
  <p>The test for a genuine Interpretive Brief: could someone without your training, your field, and your five weeks of following this beat have written this? If the answer is yes, go further. The Brief earns its place when it says something that is only possible because of what you bring. That is not expertise performed for its own sake. It is educated perception applied to a specific corner of the world you have been watching carefully.</p>
  <div class="pull">"There is a kind of knowledge that comes from looking carefully at something long enough to see what is actually there, as distinct from what you expected to see or what the summary told you was there."</div>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Week 5: Your Knowledge, Applied</h3>
  <p>Opening question: "What does this beat look like to someone with your training, and what does your training let you see that a general reader misses?" Each student completes the sentence: "What this beat is really about, when you understand [something from my field or training], is..."</p>
  <p>This week also seeds cluster formation. After the class discussion, students begin identifying whose beats raise the same underlying question, not the same surface topic, but the same deeper inquiry. The instructor reviews the discussion thread before Week 6 and proposes provisional cluster groupings of two to four students.</p>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Week 6: Clusters Confirmed</h3>
  <p>Clusters are posted before the session. The cluster's first task: agree on one sentence naming the shared question across your beats. Not the surface topics — the underlying question. Then sketch what a State of the World entry addressing that question would need to say.</p>
  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">What makes a good cluster</div>
    <p>A student following pharmaceutical pricing and a student following agricultural subsidies may share a deeper question about how public policy serves private interests. A student following local housing and a student following immigration enforcement may share a question about whose community counts when institutions decide who to protect. The cluster is not formed around topic similarity. It is formed around shared inquiry. If your shared question sentence could describe any cluster in the class, it is not yet specific enough.</p>
  </div>
</div>
</div>

