<div class="paste">Canvas Page — Interpretive Brief · Module 3 Assignment · 500–650 words · Due end of Week 6</div>
<div class="page-flag">
  <div class="page-eyebrow">Module 3 Assignment</div>
  <h1 class="page-title">Interpretive Brief</h1>
  <p class="page-deck">What your knowledge reveals that the coverage cannot say. The most important individual assignment in the module.</p>
</div>
<div class="page-rule"></div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Purpose</h3>
  <p>The Interpretive Brief is the intellectual center of this ten-week module. It asks you to say what your beat means in light of what you know, in a way the coverage itself cannot. It is not a summary of your analysis, not a reaction to the events, and not a preview of your evaluation. It is perception made precise: what a careful, educated person sees when they look at this beat that a casual reader does not.</p>
  <p>This Brief also seeds your cluster's State of the World entry. The underlying question you name at the end is the starting point for your cluster's shared work in Modules 4 and 5. Write it carefully.</p>
  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">The standard for this assignment</div>
    <p>Before submitting, ask yourself: could someone without my training, my field, and my six weeks of following this beat have written this? If the answer is yes, go further. The Brief earns its place when it says something that is only possible because of what you bring. That is the contribution. Everything else is summary.</p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Instructions: 500 to 650 words</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>What the coverage says the beat is about.</strong> One paragraph — accurately describe what mainstream coverage presents as the beat's meaning. Use Description: what does the coverage actually say?</li>
    <li><strong>What your knowledge reveals.</strong> One to two paragraphs — name the concept, framework, or field-specific understanding that changes how this beat reads. Explain it accessibly enough that a general reader can follow the logic. Then say specifically what the coverage misses or misrepresents that your training allows you to see.</li>
    <li><strong>Your interpretive claim.</strong> One paragraph — what does this beat actually mean, in light of what you know? Specific, arguable, and only possible because of what you bring to it.</li>
    <li><strong>The underlying question.</strong> One sentence — the question your interpretation opens but does not close. Specific enough to seed your cluster's shared inquiry in Modules 4 and 5.</li>
  </ol>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Rubric</h3>
  <table class="rubric">
    <tr><th>Element</th><th>Expectations</th><th>Points</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Coverage account</td><td>Accurate, specific description of what mainstream coverage presents as the beat's meaning.</td><td class="pts">15</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Disciplinary knowledge</td><td>Named, explained accessibly, applied specifically — a lens that changes what you see, not background information.</td><td class="pts">35</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Interpretive claim</td><td>Specific, arguable, and only possible because of this student's training and six weeks of beat work.</td><td class="pts">35</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Underlying question</td><td>Specific enough to seed a cluster's shared inquiry — a real open question, not a general observation about the topic.</td><td class="pts">15</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Total</strong></td><td></td><td class="pts"><strong>100</strong></td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="callout" style="margin-top:12px">
    <div class="callout-label">For instructors — return with feedback before Module 5 begins</div>
    <p>The Interpretive Brief must be returned with feedback before students begin drafting the State of the World entry. A Brief without feedback produces an entry without a genuine contribution. Brief written comments on whether the underlying question is specific enough to generate a cluster argument are the most useful feedback at this stage.</p>
  </div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- MODULE 4 OVERVIEW -->
<div class="panel" id="p-mod4">
<div class="paste">Canvas Page — Module 4 Overview · Evaluation · Weeks 7–8</div>
<div class="mod-header">
  <div class="mod-badge">Module 4 of 5</div>
  <h2 class="mod-title">Evaluation</h2>
  <p class="mod-sub">Weeks 7 and 8 — "Who bears the costs the coverage is not naming, and what does your cluster argue?"</p>
  <div class="mod-meta">
    <div class="mod-meta-item">Move <span>Evaluation</span></div>
    <div class="mod-meta-item">Weeks <span>7 and 8</span></div>
    <div class="mod-meta-item">Notebook entries <span>Two</span></div>
    <div class="mod-meta-item">Assignment <span>Equity Assessment and Cluster Proposal, due end of Week 8</span></div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>What Evaluation Is</h3>
  <p>Evaluation asks whether what is happening in your beat is fair, whether the distribution of costs and benefits is being named honestly, and whether the coverage serves the public understanding of those stakes. It is not reaction. It is a reasoned judgment, grounded in evidence, named by a principle you can state and defend, and specific about who is affected and how. The distinction matters: a reaction is what you felt when you first read the headline at Week 1. An evaluation is what you can say after seven weeks of careful attention.</p>
  <p>Module 4 runs two parallel tracks. The individual track produces the Equity Assessment, your personal evaluative argument about your beat. The cluster track produces the Cluster Proposal, your group's plan for the State of the World entry. Both are due at the end of Week 8 and both build on everything the previous modules produced.</p>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Week 7: Individual Evaluation</h3>
  <p>Opening question: "Who is bearing a cost in your beat that the coverage is not naming?" Each student names a specific affected party, not a general category but a named community, institution, or person, and the cost they are bearing. The instructor listens for evaluative claims that are specific and evidentiary rather than general and reactive.</p>
  <p>Clusters also begin sketching what their State of the World entry will argue. The distinction between describing and arguing matters here. An entry that describes what is happening in each beat is not a State of the World entry. An entry that makes a claim, one that requires all of the beats to sustain, is.</p>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Week 8: Cluster Evaluation and Planning</h3>
  <p>Opening question: "What is the civic argument your cluster's State of the World entry will make — not what it will describe, but what it will argue?" Each cluster states its argument in one sentence. The instructor pushes for specificity: an argument is something a reasonable person could disagree with on the basis of evidence.</p>
  <p>Both the Equity Assessment and the Cluster Proposal are due at the end of this week. The Equity Assessment closes the individual arc of the module. The Cluster Proposal opens the collective arc of Module 5.</p>
</div>
</div>

