<!-- MODULE 4 ASSIGNMENT -->
<div class="panel" id="p-mod4-assign">
<div class="paste">Canvas Page — Equity Assessment and Cluster Proposal · Module 4 Assignment · Due end of Week 8</div>
<div class="page-flag">
  <div class="page-eyebrow">Module 4 Assignment</div>
  <h1 class="page-title">Equity Assessment and Cluster Proposal</h1>
  <p class="page-deck">Two deliverables, due together. One closes the individual arc. One opens the collective.</p>
</div>
<div class="page-rule"></div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Part 1: Equity Assessment (Individual) — 500 to 600 words</h3>
  <p>The Equity Assessment is your structured evaluative argument about your beat. It asks you to move beyond description, analysis, and interpretation to make a reasoned judgment: about what is at stake for real people, whether the distribution of costs and benefits is fair, and whether the coverage adequately serves public understanding of those stakes.</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>The stakes.</strong> Who is affected by the developments in your beat? Name them specifically. What do they stand to gain or lose?</li>
    <li><strong>The evaluative claim.</strong> Is the distribution of costs and benefits in your beat fair or unfair, according to a principle you can name and defend? Support your claim with specific evidence from your beat work.</li>
    <li><strong>Coverage evaluation.</strong> Does your beat's coverage adequately represent the equity and ethical dimensions you have identified? What is missing, and why might it be absent?</li>
    <li><strong>The counterargument.</strong> State the strongest objection to your evaluation and respond to it substantively — not by dismissing it, but by engaging with it and saying what it adds or changes.</li>
  </ol>
  <table class="rubric" style="margin-top:12px">
    <tr><th>Element</th><th>Expectations</th><th>Points</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Stakes account</td><td>Specific, named affected parties with a concrete account of what is at stake for them.</td><td class="pts">20</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Evaluative claim</td><td>Clear claim, named principle, specific evidence — arguable and falsifiable.</td><td class="pts">30</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Coverage evaluation</td><td>Specific evaluative claim about coverage adequacy, with evidence from the four weeks of coverage work.</td><td class="pts">25</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Counterargument</td><td>Fairly stated objection and substantive response that does not simply dismiss it.</td><td class="pts">25</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Total</strong></td><td></td><td class="pts"><strong>100</strong></td></tr>
  </table>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Part 2: Cluster Proposal (Group) — 300 to 400 words</h3>
  <p>One submission per cluster. Graded on completion and specificity. A Proposal that answers all four elements with genuine specificity receives full credit.</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>The shared question.</strong> One sentence — specific enough to guide the entry and broad enough to genuinely require all beats in the cluster to answer it.</li>
    <li><strong>What each beat contributes.</strong> One sentence per beat on the irreplaceable thing it brings to the cluster argument — the angle, the knowledge, or the evidence that only that thread can supply.</li>
    <li><strong>Proposed content.</strong> What will a reader encounter in the State of the World entry? What will they understand after reading it that they did not understand before?</li>
    <li><strong>Publication plan.</strong> What pages in the physical publication will this cluster produce? What form will they take — typed text, hand-drawn elements, photographs, a combination?</li>
  </ol>
</div>
</div>

<!-- MODULE 5 OVERVIEW -->
<div class="panel" id="p-mod5">
<div class="paste">Canvas Page — Module 5 Overview · Engagement · Weeks 9–10 · Assembly Session</div>
<div class="mod-header">
  <div class="mod-badge">Module 5 of 5</div>
  <h2 class="mod-title">Engagement</h2>
  <p class="mod-sub">Weeks 9 and 10 — "What does the class say, together, about what it has been watching?"</p>
  <div class="mod-meta">
    <div class="mod-meta-item">Move <span>Engagement</span></div>
    <div class="mod-meta-item">Weeks <span>9 and 10</span></div>
    <div class="mod-meta-item">Notebook entries <span>Two, including the final entry</span></div>
    <div class="mod-meta-item">Deliverables <span>State of the World entry, physical publication, notebook archive, self-assessment</span></div>
    <div class="mod-meta-item">Assembly <span>Week 10 final session — attendance required</span></div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>What Engagement Is</h3>
  <p>Engagement is the move that asks what you do with what you know. Not what you think, not what you feel, not what you wish were true — what you actually do, in public, with the knowledge and attention you have built across nine weeks of careful work. Produce something. Carry what you have learned into a form a public audience can use. The person who has done the first four moves carefully has earned the right to say something, and has the responsibility to say it clearly, with sources, and with accountability for what they claim.</p>
  <p>In this module, engagement takes two forms: the State of the World entry, which is the written and digital record, and the physical publication, which is the thing you make by hand, in the room, together, in the last session of the module.</p>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Week 9: Drafting and Peer Review</h3>
  <p>Each cluster submits a draft State of the World entry by the middle of the week, 500 to 700 words, addressing the shared question their beats illuminate. Before submitting, run the draft through Description: what does it actually say? Does the opening deliver what it promises? Is there a gap between the shared question the cluster named and what the entry actually argues? Find the gap and close it before submitting.</p>
  <p>After submitting, each cluster reviews one other cluster's draft using the three-move structure: describe what the entry says, analyze how it works, evaluate what it needs before the assembly. Peer review is submitted as a group, 200 to 300 words, by the end of the week.</p>
  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">Peer review is not praise and it is not criticism</div>
    <p>The peer review asks: what does this entry actually say, and what does it need to say what it is trying to say? That is an editorial question, not an evaluative one. The goal is to make the entry better before the assembly, not to grade it.</p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Week 10: The Assembly Session</h3>
  <p>Final cluster entries are submitted incorporating peer review feedback. The assembly session follows. Each cluster takes three to four minutes — not to present, but to read one passage aloud from their entry and name one question their beat work left genuinely open. The room listens. After all clusters have read, the instructor or a student reads the opening of the complete assembled document aloud. Then the publication is distributed. Then it exists.</p>
  <p>The physical publication is assembled in this session from materials clusters have prepared. Pages are laid out, arranged, and combined. Each cluster contributes its section. The assembled document is photographed for the Canvas submission record. The physical copies are distributed to the class.</p>
  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">Attendance at the assembly session is required</div>
    <p>The assembly session is not something that can be made up after the fact. It is the assignment. The publication is assembled there, in that room, by the people who made the work that goes into it. If there is a genuine emergency, contact the instructor before the session.</p>
  </div>
</div>
</div>

