    <div class="journal-label">Week 9 · By Hand · 150–250 words · Photo uploaded before class</div>
    <p><strong>What I noticed:</strong> What did working with your cluster on the State of the World draft reveal about your own beat that you had not named before? What did you have to give up or revise from your individual framing to write something genuinely collective?</p>
    <p><strong>What moved:</strong> What does the cluster's draft say that none of your individual assignments said? Name it specifically.</p>
    <p><strong>What I'm sitting with:</strong> What would the draft need to say, or say differently, for a reader who knows nothing about any of your beats to find it worth reading?</p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Week 10 Entry (Final)</h3>
  <div class="journal">
    <div class="journal-label">Week 10 · By Hand · 250–350 words · Photo uploaded with full notebook archive</div>
    <p><strong>What I noticed:</strong> Read back through your notebook entries from Weeks 1 through 9 before writing this. What changed in how you see your beat? What did you believe at Week 1 that turned out to be wrong, incomplete, or more complicated than you understood?</p>
    <p><strong>What moved:</strong> What does the State of the World say that no individual assignment in this module said? What required the class, together, to make it possible?</p>
    <p><strong>What I'm sitting with:</strong> What question does your ten weeks of attention leave genuinely open — something you understand better now but have not resolved? And are you going to keep following it?</p>
  </div>
  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">On the last question</div>
    <p>The final question, are you going to keep following it, is not rhetorical. Students who say yes and mean it, who name the specific question and say something about what following it would look like, have done something the module was trying to produce. Students who say no honestly have still learned something worth knowing. Both are valid answers. What is not valid is an answer that does not actually engage with the question.</p>
  </div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- MODULE 5 DISCUSSION -->
<div class="panel" id="p-mod5-disc">
<div class="paste">Canvas Page — Module 5 Discussion Board and Peer Review · Weeks 9 and 10</div>
<div class="page-flag">
  <div class="page-eyebrow">Module 5 · Discussion and Peer Review</div>
  <h1 class="page-title">Discussion Board and Peer Review: Module 5</h1>
  <p class="page-deck">Week 9 is editorial. Week 10 is the closing conversation after the assembly.</p>
</div>
<div class="page-rule"></div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Week 9: Cluster Peer Review</h3>
  <div class="disc"><div class="disc-label">Cluster Peer Review — 200–300 words — Submitted as a group — Due end of Week 9</div><p>Your cluster has been assigned one other cluster's draft State of the World entry to review. Submit your peer review here. Address three things:<br><br><strong>Description:</strong> What does this entry actually say? State the central claim in your own words — not what it is trying to say, what it actually says on the page.<br><br><strong>Analysis:</strong> Where does the synthesis feel genuine — where does the entry say something that requires all of the beats to sustain? Where does it feel like separate pieces sitting next to each other?<br><br><strong>Editorial question:</strong> What is the one thing this entry needs to change before the assembly? Ask it as a question, not a directive.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Week 10: After the Assembly</h3>
  <div class="disc"><div class="disc-label">Your Post · 150–200 words · Due within 48 hours of the assembly session</div><p>Name one entry from a cluster that is not yours. Describe what you learned from it — specifically, something you did not know before reading it. Then name one connection between that cluster's question and your own beat that neither of you named during the module. The State of the World is complete. What did you see in it that you could not have seen before the assembly?</p></div>
  <div class="disc"><div class="disc-label">Your Reply · 75–100 words</div><p>Tell a classmate whether their open question, the one they are leaving the module with, is one you share. If it is: why does it matter that it remains open? If it is not: what is different about how you are framing yours?</p></div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- MODULE 5 ASSIGNMENT -->
<div class="panel" id="p-mod5-assign">
<div class="paste">Canvas Page — State of the World and Physical Publication · Module 5 Assignment · Due at Assembly Session · Week 10</div>
<div class="page-flag">
  <div class="page-eyebrow">Module 5 Assignment</div>
  <h1 class="page-title">State of the World and the Physical Publication</h1>
  <p class="page-deck">The culminating deliverables. One is a written document submitted to Canvas. One is a physical object assembled in the room and distributed to the class.</p>
</div>
<div class="page-rule"></div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>The State of the World Entry (Cluster Submission) — 500 to 700 words</h3>
  <p>The State of the World entry is the piece of writing that exists because this specific group of people followed these specific beats at this specific moment and then looked at what they found together. It is not a collection of individual summaries. It is a collective argument, one that requires all of the cluster's beats to sustain, and that could not have been made by any one person alone.</p>
  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">The standard for this entry</div>
    <p>Before submitting, ask: could a reader who has never heard of any of these beats encounter this entry and find it worth reading? Does it make a claim rather than simply describe a situation? Does it draw on the evidence of all the beats in the cluster? Does it say something that ten weeks of collective attention made possible? If the answer to any of these is no, revise before submitting.</p>
  </div>
  <table class="rubric" style="margin-top:14px">
    <tr><th>Element</th><th>Expectations</th><th>Points</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Collective argument</td><td>Makes a claim, not just a description of a situation. Requires all beats in the cluster to sustain it.</td><td class="pts">30</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Evidence and specificity</td><td>Claims grounded in ten weeks of beat work. Specific — no vague generalities about the topic.</td><td class="pts">20</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Accessibility</td><td>Readable by someone outside the class with no prior knowledge of any beat in the cluster.</td><td class="pts">20</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Peer feedback incorporated</td><td>Week 9 draft meaningfully revised in response to peer review, not cosmetically adjusted.</td><td class="pts">15</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Description applied</td><td>Entry says what it claims to say. The opening earns what it promises.</td><td class="pts">15</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Total</strong></td><td></td><td class="pts"><strong>100</strong></td></tr>
  </table>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>The Notebook Archive and Self-Assessment</h3>
  <p>Submit all ten notebook entries compiled into a single document — photographs in chronological order, each labeled by week. The notebook is assessed holistically: not entry by entry, but as evidence of sustained genuine engagement with a live beat across ten weeks, and of developing observation and analysis over time.</p>
  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">Holistic grading standard</div>
    <p>Complete and genuinely engaged across all ten weeks with evidence of developing thought: full credit. Mostly complete with some thin or summary-style entries: 80 percent. Significant gaps or entries clearly written for compliance rather than observation: 60 percent. Incomplete: no credit on the notebook component.</p>
  </div>
  <p>The self-assessment is submitted with the notebook archive. Answer these six questions, one per move plus the analog practice. A sentence or two each, more if you have more to say.</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Description:</strong> What did you believe about your beat at Week 1 that turned out to be wrong, incomplete, or more complicated than you understood?</li>
    <li><strong>Analysis:</strong> What structural pattern in your beat's coverage could you name by Week 4 that you could not have named before following it?</li>
    <li><strong>Interpretation:</strong> What is the most specific thing your training lets you see in your beat that a general reader would miss? Name it precisely.</li>
    <li><strong>Evaluation:</strong> Who bore a cost in your beat that the coverage did not name adequately? What would the coverage have needed to include for the public to understand what was actually at stake?</li>
    <li><strong>Engagement:</strong> What does the State of the World entry argue that none of your individual assignments argued? What required the cluster to make it possible?</li>
    <li><strong>The notebook:</strong> What is the most specific thing you noticed — and wrote down by hand — that you would not have noticed if you had been reading your beat casually, without the notebook practice?</li>
  </ol>
</div>
</div>

<!-- AI THREAD -->
<div class="panel" id="p-ai-thread">
<div class="paste">Persistent Canvas Page — AI Observation Thread · One thread, runs all ten weeks · Do not duplicate per week</div>
<div class="page-flag">
  <div class="page-eyebrow">Persistent Thread — All Ten Weeks</div>
  <h1 class="page-title">The AI Observation Thread</h1>
  <p class="page-deck">One thread. Ten weeks. A class record of how AI is actually operating in the information environment you navigate.</p>
</div>
<div class="page-rule"></div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>What This Is</h3>
  <p>This is a single discussion thread that runs across the entire module. Do not create a new thread each week. Any time you encounter AI's visible role in how a news item was generated, summarized, recommended, or distributed, add one observation here. One sentence on what you found. One sentence on how you knew — or how you were not sure. No argument required. No conclusion needed. Just the observation, as specific as you can make it.</p>
  <p>Examples of what to add: an AI summary in a search result that said something different from the article it was summarizing, and what specifically was different. A story that appeared to be AI-generated based on something specific you noticed in the writing or sourcing. A recommendation pattern in your feed that seemed to be amplifying a story in a way that felt disproportionate to its importance. A source that turned out not to exist when you tried to verify it. A moment when the AI-generated overview of a topic you know well got something importantly wrong.</p>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Why This Thread Matters</h3>
  <p>Over ten weeks, this thread becomes something more useful than any single reading about AI and media could be: a specific, varied, first-hand record of how AI is operating in the information environment this particular class is navigating, in these particular beats, during this particular period. The observations accumulate. Patterns emerge. By Week 8 or 9, the thread tells a story that none of its individual entries could tell alone.</p>
  <p>The instructor reads this thread and brings observations from it into the class conversation — not as a lesson, but as a contribution. "Someone added to the AI thread this week that..." and then the class runs the three moves on it together. The thread is a gift the class gives itself. Use it.</p>
</div>
</div>

<!-- PUBLICATION GUIDE -->
<div class="panel" id="p-pub-guide">
<div class="paste">Canvas Page — Physical Publication Guide · Reference for Students and Instructors · All versions</div>
<div class="page-flag">
  <div class="page-eyebrow">Reference Page — The Physical Publication</div>
  <h1 class="page-title">Making the Slow News Publication</h1>
  <p class="page-deck">Everything you need to know about the physical deliverable: the format, what goes in it, how to assemble it, and what you submit to Canvas.</p>
</div>
<div class="page-rule"></div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Why Physical</h3>
  <p>The physical publication is not a digital project printed out. It is assembled by hand, in the room, by the people who made the work that goes into it. It exists because a specific group of people followed specific beats at a specific moment and then sat down together to make something from what they found. That is not something an algorithm produces. It is not something AI generates. It is something a class makes.</p>
  <p>The format is flexible because the form should follow the work. An 11-by-17 sheet folded once becomes a four-page tabloid. Opened flat in landscape, it is a broadsheet spread. Opened flat in portrait, it is a magazine page. An 8.5-by-11 page is the atomic unit: one entry, one week of attention, one page. The publication is what the class makes from those units, assembled in whatever format the instructor specifies.</p>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>The 20-Page Version</h3>
  <p>In a ten-week course with two class sessions per week, there are twenty class meetings. The full version of the Slow News publication is designed with one page per class session: twenty pages, made across twenty sessions, assembled on the twentieth. That is the ideal. Not all courses will reach twenty pages, and that is fine. What matters is that the publication is a genuine record of the quarter's work, not assembled at the last minute from material produced specifically for the deadline, but drawn from the notebooks, the beat work, and the State of the World entries that have been building all term.</p>
  <p>Each cluster contributes a section. Each notebook contributes material. The class contributes the conversation that happened in the room over ten weeks. The publication is the record of all three.</p>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>What Goes In It</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>The State of the World entries, one per cluster, the anchoring pieces</li>
    <li>Notebook excerpts, selected by each student, hand-transcribed or photographed and printed</li>
    <li>Headlines and annotations made by hand directly on the page with pen or marker</li>
    <li>Typed text for longer pieces, printed and cut and pasted in physically, with visible edges and seams intact</li>
    <li>Photographs from the term, printed and placed by hand</li>
    <li>Found materials from beats: clipped headlines from physical newspapers, printed primary documents, anything that belongs to the story that was followed</li>
    <li>Hand-drawn elements: diagrams, maps, illustrations, anything that helps communicate what was found</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">On design</div>
    <p>The publication does not need to look designed. It needs to look made. The difference is important. A designed object has been optimized for visual coherence. A made object carries the evidence of the people who made it: handwriting at different angles, paste lines visible, drawings that are clearly by hand. The seams and imperfections are not flaws in the Slow News publication. They are evidence of its authenticity.</p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>The Assembly Session</h3>
  <p>Come prepared with your cluster's materials: the printed State of the World entry, your selected notebook excerpts, your photographs, and any physical materials from your beat. The session has three phases.</p>
  <p><strong>Assembly (approximately 30 minutes):</strong> Clusters work at tables. Pages are laid out, materials are arranged, text is pasted, and drawings are added. The instructor circulates. The noise of making things in a room together is the right noise for this session.</p>
  <p><strong>Reading aloud (approximately 15 minutes):</strong> Each cluster reads one passage from their entry and names one open question their beat work left genuinely unresolved. The room listens without devices open. This is the coffee klatch the whole module has been building toward.</p>
  <p><strong>Distribution (approximately 5 minutes):</strong> The assembled publication is distributed, one copy per student where printing allows. The instructor or a student reads the opening of the complete document aloud. Then the session ends.</p>
</div>
<div class="block">
  <h3>Submission to Canvas</h3>
  <p>After the assembly session, photograph the complete publication with care — each spread or page as a separate image, in order, with enough light to read the handwritten text clearly. Upload the complete image set to Canvas as your Module 5 submission. The physical object is yours to keep. The photograph set is the formal submission record and the digital archive of what the class made.</p>
</div>
</div>

